    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="143"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d143">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 661.119/115</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Miles</persName> of the Division of
                        Near Eastern Affairs, of the Department of State, to the Director of the
                        Bureau of Exports, War Trade Board</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Van Sinderen</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 8, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. <persName>Van Sinderen</persName>
                    </hi>: I have your letter of March 6, regarding cargo on the steamer <hi
                        rend="italic">Nippon</hi> to be reexported apparently from Shanghai to
                        Vladivostok.<note n="1" xml:id="d143fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I understand the Department approves of no licenses for export by private firms
                    unless the destination is proved in advance to be one which will safeguard the
                    shipment from falling into German hands or serving German purposes. Furthermore,
                    it has been decided to hold in abeyance all licenses for Russia for the present
                    and until the situation clears up a little.</p>
                <p>I would be interested in knowing to whom these supplies are to be reexported.</p>
                <p>Yours very sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Basil Miles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
